Britain didn't offer the British Isles in return for Lend-Lease.  In fact they declined that deal and made their own counter-offer.  The negotiations to work out the contract for those 50 destroyers were nothing more than an international haggling session.  The Brits basically wanted the destroyers for nothing, and the US came to the table with the most outlandish deal they could come up with.  <br>
<br>
The compromise ended up being a fair deal in the end, but the two sides of the table had to start somewhere.  The Americans very likely didn't expect to get the British West Indies in return for 50 destroyers (but if the Brits ad said OK, the guy who came up with the idea would have been a political hero), and the offer very likely reflects that they had no real idea how desperate the British Empire was.  This was an attempt to get a feel for how the British stood...to answer the question &quot;how badly do they want 50 destroyers?&quot;<br>
<br>
As for what Charles Lindburgh said...yeah that's interesting.  Couple of things.  First, his statement about not being able to fit enough airplanes on the British Isles doesn't seem to fit his character...until you realize that a) he either wrote that in as a gross overstatement for the sake of the argument, or b) he's a civilian after all, and probably had no access to information about the strength of the Luftwaffe (the planes on the continent).  It's interesting if you consider this point...it reflects the popular opinion in 1941 that the German Air Force was undefeatable, and must have had an infinite number of aircraft.<br>
<br>
The truth of the matter was that Germany was heavily engaged in the Soviet Union at the time, having just launched the largest offensive in world history (the record still holds) in June 1941.  The invasion of Britain had been indefinitely postponed the previous autumn, and in fact there were only 2 (3? don't have my references to know for sure) Jagdgeschwader on the west coast of Europe..elements of JG 26, JG 54, and I think JG 1 or 2.  That's about 200-300ish aircraft altogether defending the continent from air attack from the west.  The British had at least double that number available for air operations out of southeastern Britain alone. All other elements of the Luftwaffe were committed to Barbarossa (invasion of USSR), plus elements of 1 or 2 Jagdgeschwader flying around in North Africa where Rommel was just starting to cause havoc for the British.  Formal daytime raids of Britain had long since stopped by this time:  Small, tactical attacks being carried out by low-flying fighter-bombers on military and civilian targets in southeastern Britain.<br>
<br>
The interesting thing is that Britain knew all of this....or at least had a good feel for things.  I could be wrong, but I'm pretty sure that Ultra had, by this time, succeeded in cracking the German communications code.  This wasn't the sort of information that they would give to the Americans...at least, not until later that year when America entered the war.  In fact, very few people even in Britain knew about this.  It was one of the best-kept secrets of the war.  I'm pretty sure, however, that the negotiators at the Lend-Lease bargaining table at least knew of it, and thus had an &quot;ace up their sleeve,&quot; so-to-speak.<br>
<br>
It's also interesting to note that fairly soon after Lend-Lease started up, the Russians would begin screaming for help and would begin receiving aid from America, too.  Also don't forget the aid provided to China in their fight against Japan.  It seems the only people not receiving aid in 1941 were the Axis powers.<br>
<br>
The only problem area that really worried the British at this time was the huge amount of supplies and materiel being sent to the bottom fo the Atlantic by German U-boats.  There was a real concern the Britain would be starved out of the war *before the Americans could enter it*.  Hence the need for those 50 destroyers.  Yes, the British definitely believed America would eventually enter the war...it was only a question of when.  Heck, even in the days following the attack on Pearl Harbor, there was the question of how to get America into the European conflict (question by both American and British politicians).  This was fortunately answered by Hitler, who declared war on the US shortly after America declared war on Japan.<br>
<br>
Anyway, yeah...this doesn't belong in flames, but hey...there was a lot of fire in WWII.<br>
